<p>A pay stub template is a structured document that shows the breakdown of an employee's wages for a specific pay period. Every pay stub, regardless of the format, contains the same core elements: employer information, employee information, pay period dates, gross earnings, itemized deductions, and net pay. The question is how you get from a blank template to a completed, accurate document.</p>

<p>You have two approaches. You can start with a blank document in Word, Excel, or Google Docs and fill in every field manually, calculating the taxes yourself. Or you can use a generator like this one that does the tax math automatically and produces a professional PDF in seconds. Both approaches work -- but they have meaningfully different tradeoffs that are worth understanding before you choose.</p>

<h2>Why a Generator Beats a Static Template in Almost Every Case</h2>

<p>The appeal of a Word or Excel template is obvious: it looks like a pay stub, you download it, you fill in the numbers, you are done. The problem is that the template does not know any tax laws. It does not know that 2024 federal income tax brackets start at 10% and top out at 37%. It does not know that Social Security is 6.2% up to $168,600 in 2024 but stops there. It does not know whether your state has a flat tax or a graduated one, what the rate is this year, or whether there are special deductions like California's SDI or Washington's WA Cares Fund.</p>

<p>You have to calculate all of that yourself and type the numbers into the template. If you use the wrong bracket, type the wrong percentage, or forget a deduction, the stub will have errors. And here is the risk: a landlord or lender who checks the math on your stub and finds it does not add up will question everything about the document. Accurate numbers are not just about precision -- they are about credibility.</p>

<p>A generator eliminates all of this. You enter gross pay, choose your state, select your pay frequency, and the calculator applies the current, correct tax rates automatically. The output is a PDF with professional formatting, accurate numbers, and all the fields a landlord, lender, or employer expects to see.</p>

<h2>When a Static Template Still Makes Sense</h2>

<p>There are situations where a downloaded template is appropriate. If you need a blank form for reference -- to understand what fields go on a pay stub, to show an employee what their expected pay breakdown will look like before running formal payroll, or to create a visual template that your own payroll system can use -- a static document works fine. Templates also work for situations where all the numbers are pre-calculated and you simply need a place to put them.</p>

<p>For generating actual income documentation that will be submitted to a landlord, lender, or other party, use a generator. The risk of calculation errors on a static template is too high.</p>

<h2>Limitations of Word and Excel Templates</h2>

<p>Word templates for pay stubs have significant limitations that are worth understanding:</p>

<p><strong>No formula logic:</strong> A Word document is purely a formatting tool. Every number you enter is a static value -- there is no way to embed a formula that automatically calculates federal tax withholding using the current year's brackets. You calculate everything in your head or on a separate calculator, then type the results. Each number is an independent entry with no validation against any other number.</p>

<p><strong>Format breakage:</strong> Pay stub templates in Word often break when the values entered do not fit the cell sizes. A long employer name, a high dollar amount, or more than two lines of address can throw off the entire table layout. Fixing these formatting issues requires Word expertise that many people do not have.</p>

<p><strong>No year-to-date tracking:</strong> A complete pay stub shows year-to-date (YTD) totals for each category -- total gross paid so far this year, total taxes withheld to date, etc. A Word template has no memory of previous stubs, so you must manually calculate and enter YTD totals for every stub you create. Generating multiple stubs for multiple pay periods means maintaining your own running totals separately and typing them in each time.</p>

<p><strong>Outdated tax rates:</strong> A template you download today may have been created with 2022 or 2023 tax brackets. Federal brackets adjust for inflation each year. If you use a template with last year's brackets, your federal tax calculation will be wrong. The generator in this tool uses current-year rates and is updated annually.</p>

<h2>All Required Fields on a Complete Pay Stub</h2>

<p>Whether you use a template or a generator, a complete pay stub needs these fields:</p>

<p><strong>Employer section:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Employer's full legal name</li>
  <li>Employer's address (street, city, state, zip)</li>
  <li>Employer's EIN (Employer Identification Number) -- optional for self-generated, required for formal payroll</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Employee section:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Employee's full legal name (as it appears on tax documents)</li>
  <li>Employee's address -- not always required but common</li>
  <li>Employee's SSN (typically last 4 digits for security)</li>
  <li>Employee ID (if applicable)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Pay period:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Pay period start date</li>
  <li>Pay period end date</li>
  <li>Pay date (the date wages are distributed)</li>
  <li>Pay frequency (weekly, bi-weekly, semi-monthly, monthly)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Earnings:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Regular earnings (with hours and rate for hourly workers)</li>
  <li>Overtime earnings (shown separately with OT hours and OT rate)</li>
  <li>Any additional earnings (bonuses, commissions, tips, shift differentials)</li>
  <li>Gross pay total</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Deductions:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Federal income tax withheld</li>
  <li>Social Security tax (6.2%)</li>
  <li>Medicare tax (1.45%)</li>
  <li>State income tax (if applicable)</li>
  <li>Any state-specific deductions (CA SDI, WA Cares Fund, NY PFL, NJ DI, etc.)</li>
  <li>Voluntary pre-tax deductions (health insurance, 401k, HSA, FSA)</li>
  <li>Voluntary post-tax deductions (Roth 401k, supplemental insurance, union dues)</li>
  <li>Total deductions</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Net pay and YTD:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Net pay for the period</li>
  <li>Year-to-date gross pay</li>
  <li>Year-to-date total deductions by category</li>
  <li>Year-to-date net pay</li>
</ul>

