<h2>Why the Generator Beats Any Static Template</h2>

<p>Any static Word, Excel, or Google Docs template requires you to calculate everything manually. Here's what that looks like for a $75,000/year salaried employee: you must compute $2,884.62 bi-weekly gross, then apply 2024 bracket math: annualize $75,000, subtract $14,600 standard deduction = $60,400 taxable; 10% on $11,600 = $1,160; 12% on $35,550 = $4,266; 22% on $13,250 = $2,915; total annual federal tax $8,341; per period $320.81. Then Social Security: $2,884.62 x 6.2% = $178.85. Medicare: $2,884.62 x 1.45% = $41.83. Net approximately $2,292.80 before state. Then update YTD columns for each line item for every subsequent stub. One wrong formula and every stub is wrong. IncomeRecord.com does this automatically in real time, updates for tax year changes, and produces a PDF formatted exactly the way lenders and landlords expect.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Pay Stub Templates</h2>

<h3>Is a generated pay stub the same as a pay stub from a payroll company?</h3>
<p>Functionally, yes. A pay stub generated by this tool contains all the same fields as one generated by ADP, Paychex, or a large corporate payroll system. The format is slightly different (each payroll company has its own layout), but the information content is identical. Landlords and lenders are not checking which payroll system generated your stub -- they are checking that the fields are present, the numbers are consistent, and the math adds up.</p>

<h3>How many pay stubs do I need to provide for an apartment application?</h3>
<p>Most landlords ask for the two to three most recent pay stubs. Some ask for one month's worth of stubs, some ask for the last 30-60 days, and some ask for the last three months. For documentation purposes, generate stubs covering at least 60 days of pay periods. See our <a href="/pay-stub-for-apartment">pay stub for apartment</a> guide for specifics on what different property managers require and how to present your stubs effectively.</p>

<h3>Do templates work for both salaried and hourly workers?</h3>
<p>Yes, but the fields and calculations are different. Salaried workers have consistent gross pay per period (annual salary divided by pay periods), no hour tracking required, and the same deductions every period. Hourly workers must show hours worked, overtime separately, and their gross pay varies based on hours. The templates linked above are specific to each type.</p>

<h3>Can I use a pay stub template for a mortgage application?</h3>
<p>Pay stubs are one part of a mortgage application's income documentation package. Lenders typically require pay stubs plus W-2 forms plus bank statements. For W-2 employees, recent pay stubs and last two years of W-2s are standard. For self-employed borrowers, lenders want two years of tax returns plus a YTD profit and loss statement. See our <a href="/pay-stub-for-mortgage">pay stub for mortgage</a> guide for complete details on what underwriters actually review.</p>

<h3>What's the difference between the generator on this page and the state-specific generators?</h3>
<p>The generator on this page defaults to California tax rates. If you are in a different state, use the state-specific page to get the correct state income tax calculation automatically. For example, the <a href="/texas-pay-stub-generator">Texas pay stub generator</a> shows no state income tax; the <a href="/new-york-pay-stub-generator">New York pay stub generator</a> applies New York's 4%-10.9% graduated rates. Each state page has content specific to that state's laws and economy.</p>

